de](https://www.benzinga.com/markets/options/20/04/15836145/tony-zhang-breaks-down-an-interesting-caesars-entertainment-options-trade)\n\n**Technology & Ecommerce**\n\n\u00b7 A good chunk of the population receives their relief checks, tax returns, and those who are still employed have amassed a ton of savings to spend on online shopping. Macy\u2019s, Shopify, Etsy are among the ones to report positive earnings in Q2\n\n\u00b7 Facebook (thanks to IG) & Netflix report record highs due to influx of new users and subscribers. Their ad revenues, which make up a good chunk of their revenue, go off the roof\n\n\u00b7 Zoom Technologies and Cisco go through a small correction as less people start using it\n\n\u00b7 Thermal imaging devices that Flir produces become widely adopted at airports to avoid the second wave of the virus\n\n\u00b7 Ed-Tech companies\u2019 stocks soar. Arco Platform Limited (NYSE:ARCE), which delivers educational content to private schools, students report record earnings. Instructure, Inc. (NYSE:INST) and Perdoceo Education Corporation (PRDO) are others that see highs by mid-July\n\n**Food & Beverage**\n\n\u00b7 Alcohol companies beat their earnings as quarantine drinking exceeds regular consumption levels. Weather gets warmer and people want to slowly celebrate post quarantine with beer, liquor and wine\n\n\u00b7 Companies like Diageo and Constellation Brands, AV InBev and Brown-Forman recover quickly from the crisis\n\n\u00b7 Kroger (NYSE:KR) is one of the few names that are still positive for the year and for good reason. As a pivotal necessity in any circumstance, KR stock represents consistent demand due to its sophisticated preservation and distribution capabilities\n\n\u00b7 Costco (NYSE:COST) surprisingly beats its rivals. Average Costco shopper typically makes about $100,000 a year and this makes the company more resilient to economic downturns. When things bounce back in summer, Costco will continue enjoy strong demand\n\n**Biotech**\n\n\u00b7 Abbott (NYSE:ABT) announces that it is launching the final test for SARS-CoV-2 -- and its first antibody test for the coronavirus. In addition, Moderna beats Gilead in building the vaccine for the treatment and gets FDA approval in fall for distribution\n\n\u00b7 Chinese-made coronavirus antibody tests become available in the U.S. thanks to tiny Aytu Bioscience  (NYSE:AYTU). The company beats its competitors in diagnosis accuracy and becomes a winner in the anybody race\n\nI don't know much about banking or finance, so I've omitted that one. Feel free to share your thoughts below.", "created_utc": 1587504127.0, "permalink": "/r/wallstreetbets/comments/g5o02v/postcovid19_world_bets_ticker_compilation/", "is_self": true}